segments.text: Let me set this up here.
Brief biographical sketch of yourself and your schooling.
Do I need to give my name and everything?
Sure.
OK. Name's Sterling Wheeler.
Brief biographical sketch, starting with schooling only.
Sounds OK. Just schooling at Texas A&E.
I've got my bachelor's in environmental design there in 77.
Received my master's in urban planning
in 79.
And to give you history before that, I was born and raised in South Texas, Corpus Christi.
And then after my schooling, I ended up in Dallas.
And I've been here a year and a half.
Basically, there's not a whole lot to say.
OK.
Which of these questions do you think you could best cover?
How about number nine?
Do you know how many planters are now employed?
That fluctuates somewhat.
I could check on that.
I have to go ask our clerk.
You want me to go check on that now?
I could get that for you.
The department, I think, has around 80 people, but I don't know how many of those are professionals.
at least 40 to 50, somewhere in there, but I can get an exact number.
We've had a couple people leave recently.
Three people leave.
Okay.
Is there any systematic periodic review of your city's comp plan?
We don't have a comp plan, and therefore there's no periodic review.
Okay, so... Then...
Obviously, since your city does not conduct comprehensive planning, how would you characterize this planning stuff?
For example, incremental or radical?
What is radical planning?
That's a .
I guess it's incremental planning.
We are reactionary.
We don't really plan for problems.
If a problem occurs or an issue comes up, we then initiate a study.
Most of our studies are initiated through either the planning commission stating that there's a problem.
Therefore, you, the planning department, have to study the problem and come up with recommendations.
And that usually comes out of zoning cases, sometimes subdivision cases, but seldom subdivision cases.
Or the city council thinks there's a problem.
And they tell the planning commission, who relays it to us, we do a study.
Or we see there's a problem and we ask the planning commission if we can initiate a study, or we initiate it on our own.
An example is our only adopted land use plan, which is the Kleberg Community.
plan, which that's the first plan I worked on when I came here.
It was initiated when the city consolidated with the former city of Kleberg.
We had to solve some zoning questions.
Kleberg had its own zoning ordinance.
As part of the state statute of consolidation, you have to adopt
that city's ordinances for a period of time during a transition period.
So we adopted Kleberg's ordinance.
And it wasn't real compatible with the Dallas ordinance, so we conducted a land use study to determine proper zoning of the area.
So we did a little land use study, got citizen participation,
As a result, we had a land use plan.
And based on the land use plan, we developed a zoning proposal and changed Kleberg zoning to Dallas zoning, essentially.
That's basically how we operate.
It's reactionary.
We really don't have any type of comprehensive or long-range outlook at this time.
We would like to, and our work program was geared into developing a comprehensive plan over the next three years.
But we had some budget, severe budget cuts this past year.
I think we lost $150,000 out of our budget, resulting in losing three positions.
So that sort of put us off of our three-year timetable of getting something out.

And what even makes it look a little worse in terms of if we're going to get a comprehensive plan out is this upcoming tax referendum, which might totally not abolish the planning department, but severely cut it.
I haven't directly answered that.
that question but we really don't do any comprehensive planning at this time but we do, that's one of our objectives is to eventually get into a comprehensive planning process.
But right now it's not feasible from a political standpoint and from a budgetary standpoint it's probably not feasible because
We have too many little short-range projects that we're given, which really doesn't allow us to have a long-range viewpoint that we're trying.
I'll reword this question a bit.
What administrative procedures and planning program elements does your community have for implementing?
We don't have a community plan, just planning.
Which one?
Seven.
Seven?
Program elements are the departments organized, I think, in six or seven divisions, and each one is considered a program.
My division is land use and public facilities.
In this program, we usually try to handle all the land use issues that are broad in nature, affect an area of the community like North Dallas,
an area larger than what's considered a neighborhood.
Then we have another program area, neighborhood and community development.
That handles the department's involvement in CD monies, which basically spin on doing neighborhood studies.
Then we have urban design and the environment section, which is Tom Niederhauer's section.
And that handles all the historical designation processing.
It staffs some environmental committee.
I'm not familiar with what it is, the actual title.
It staffs the sign board.
Well, I think that's been shifted.
The sign board has been shifted to
Zoning and Development Administration.
That's another program aspect.

The Zoning and Development Administration is basically our processing division, where it processes zoning cases, subdivision cases, Board of Adjustment cases, floodplain fill applications, signed Board of Adjustment.
Then we have an Economic Analysis Division.

which basically handles our computer work, where we're putting together a database, looking at how, or utilizing the database we have in the city, like looking at the tax file, seeing how we can utilize that, the building permit file, getting it in a format that we can use, taking other departments' information and trying to build up a database that we can use.
easily so we can punch in some information and get it out in a form that we can use.
So in terms of program elements, it sort of matches up with our divisional organization.
Have I answered your question or am I beating around the bush?
Yeah, I think so.

What organizational structure do you have in its relationship with the, you mentioned it just then about the different program elements, but the relationship with the city council or other legislative body?
And how is the relationship with the city council?
Okay, we have no direct relationship with the city council.
It's in the city charter that staff cannot directly communicate with the city council.
The only communication directly with the city council that's allowed is through the city manager.
We are allowed direct communication with the city planning commission.
But usually that communication is usually transferred through a program manager or an assistant director or the director.
It's usually not a staff individual.
The only cases where the individual staff that has the most communication in our department with the planning commission are the zoning planners.
And they basically present each zoning case to the planning commission.
And the only time other staff members have communication with the Planning Commission is when they work with them on subcommittees.
We have a zoning ordinance review committee, which has one or two commission members on it.
We have a new inner city committee looking at inner city issues.
There's one or two commission members on that.
That's the only time we really get direct contact with commission members.
So it's sort of a formal structure, whereas

We communicate with our program manager who communicates with the assistant director and director, and the assistant director and directors have basic communication with the planning commission and the manager's office.
Sort of a hierarchy.
Whereas there is communication every once in a while in between individual staff members and the planning commission, but it's not very often.
Like I just recently gave a presentation to the planning commission, and one of them asked if I was new, because they never saw me.
They only see about 10 different people regularly in the department, and some of them assume that's basically it.
That's the whole department, those people they see once a week.
Because I've been here a year and a half, and this lady said, oh, are you new?
Where have you been?
So in terms of organizations, pretty formal in terms of who has direct contact with the people higher up.
Because the city is rather large.
Our department's rather large.
And you can't have every member in the department having contact with every member of the planning commission.
It would create chaos.
And that'd be mixed stories.
One staff member would have an opinion, and he'd express that opinion to a commission member, and the commission member would take that as the department's position when it's not.
So that would lead to problems if you didn't have that formal line of communication, whereas communication usually comes through very few people to the higher level.
What's the present city council's reaction to planning, if you know what I mean?
I've read many a North Dallas issue.
Overall, I don't think they're very responsive.
There's a few members that seem to be, like Sid Stahl seems to want planning, wants a comprehensive plan.
I think the council's sort of divided now.
They have divided interest.
I think we're in a transition from a developer or business-oriented council to a people-oriented council.
Or maybe not a people-oriented council, but a district-oriented council, because we just recently changed over to single-member districts.
whereas most of the council members are looking out after their constituency, which is sometimes a minority constituency, like Medrano's constituency is probably mostly ethnics.
I can't state that as facts, but I think it's sort of dividing the city up into areas and creating a lot of little squabbles that wouldn't have occurred if all the council members were at large.

It is changing the structure of the council and its relationship to the business community, but still the council is very strongly associated with the business community because Paulson's a big developer in town and he's the mayor.
It's sort of a traditional pattern that the council would be business-oriented or development-oriented.
pro-development oriented.
It's not to say development's bad, it's just it's probably bad when the decision makers are all biased when they're making a decision.
So it's really hard to tell the direction they're going to take in terms of planning.
There are too many unknowns that elections coming up, Folsom isn't running for re-election.
If we get a strong mayor in there that's people-oriented, it'll probably change the outlook tremendously.
Then again, we don't know what's going to happen in the tax referendum.
If that passes, even if we do get a council that is pro-planning, we're not going to be able to do any planning because we're not going to have the staff.
That is, I assume we're not going to have the staff.
So it's really hard to tell where we're going to be going until after January 17th, or 18th, whenever that election is.
Why don't we skip down to the last question?
You mentioned the history part would be hard for you to cover, which would be mostly what 11 is.
And you've answered what the current status of planning is in the city.
How about the role of outside consultants in planning?
I really don't know how much impact outside consultants have.
Anytime we get a controversial issue, it seems that we bring in a consultant to do a study instead of staff handling it.
In many cases, it's not always.
I really haven't had that much experience with consultants while I've been here.
Everything I've worked on, we haven't had a consultant.
I came in at the tail end of one consultant study and took it through.
That was Babcock did an analysis of our zoning ordinance.
And one aspect of that was analysis of our parking standards in the zoning ordinance.
And as a result of that, one of my functions when I first got here was to
staffed the zoning advisory committee and put together some recommendations based on Babcock's parking study or parking analysis.
In most cases, we disagreed with what Babcock did.
That was the poorest part of his study.
But I really don't know how involved consultants have been with the city.
Tom Niederhammer would know.
He probably already told Cornish what their involvement is because he's worked quite a bit with people like Kevin Lynch, who did our sign ordinance and worked with our sign ordinance committee.
So Tom would have a better viewpoint of how the role of consultants have affected planning in Dallas.
OK, how about on question number 12, these influences?
You mentioned the political influence or the business orientation.
Have you noticed any religious influences which affected planning for you?
I really don't think there has been significant religious influences on planning.
I think political is probably the biggest current influence on where planning will go.
Geographic influence had probably been the strongest in determining the urban form in Dallas in terms of why Dallas came about, why Dallas occurred here, and why it grew.
It's significant now in terms of being a regional center.
It was significant back in the 1800s because this was the narrowest crossing of the Trinity within 100 miles.
That's the reason why Bryan came here in the first place.
It's probably the reason why the railroads were enclosed to come here.
Also because of some bribery that went on and stuff.
Which all these things added up to Dallas growing.
It has regional significance.
So I think that's important in its early development and its current status as being a regional distribution center for goods.
It's probably the reason why the World Trade Center out here is doing so well.
The reason why it can compete with New York in terms of marketing fashion and stuff because of its centralized location.
So the most important effect on planning is political.
Geographic location is important as far as its early development.
I'm not too familiar with sociological effects or ethnic effects.
groups are a political force, so they relate to the political climate.
But I don't know about what their effects on planning is, other than they're sort of skeptical.
Anytime we'd go into an area,

that's dominated by an ethnic group, they're very skeptical of what we're doing because they see us as being the big city and seeing us as a foe because we've done so many bad things to them in the past, putting freeways through the middle of their neighborhoods.
They're afraid that we're going to go in there and tear down their whole area and they won't have any place to live.
And that was one of the reasons why the...
ICP plan, the Interim Comprehensive Plans, failed because you couldn't get the minority support.
And the minorities were the ones to benefit from a planning effort.
So I guess they do affect planning somewhat.
If they're not receptive to planning, the planning probably won't occur because you need citizen support

or the planning effort, and the citizen support relates directly to political climate, like if there's strong citizen support in the planning department doing something, it's more than likely that the politicians will be somewhat in favor of what we're doing.
And that's one reason why any time we do a land use study, or most of the time we go out and

try to put together some citizen participation, have a community meeting, elect a task force to work with us so we can go through the public hearing process, have citizens there that worked with us as evidence that we were out in the community working with the citizens and that we have their support.
It's much easier to get things through.
So I guess if you're working in an area that's composed of minorities, you're going to have to have their support more than likely.
to get a plan through, if it's a neighborhood or community plan.
Do you see any military influences anywhere?
From my experiences in Fort Worth, it's pretty much now.
Well, in the early 60s and 70s, there was a bomb in enforcement.
It's dying out now.
Do you see any in the Dallas area?
I don't know if there has been or not.
I'd say currently there isn't any.
We do have a naval base out way on the... Grand Prairie.
Yeah, it's in our city limits, but essentially it's surrounded by Grand Prairie.
But I don't see that as a big influence on the city of Dallas.
It's way out there on the edge.
I don't know what kind of impact it has had.
I think that's the only military installation in the city that I know of.
How about the... What do you see as the big economic influence in the area?
now and in the coming future?
I think the one thing that has had a major economic influence on the city and its direction of growth is the creation of DFW.
That has strengthened the growth to the northwest.
That's the only area the city's really growing in.
Look at a growth corridor.
We're growing in between here and north out of Dallas.
And if that airport wasn't built, I don't think you'd be seeing that kind of growth.
I don't think north Dallas would have grown as it did because it seems to be correlated to DFW being built.
But I can't say that's a fact.
I'm not.
that familiar with regional economics.
That's just a general observation.
Well, has the city of Dallas come up with, I shouldn't say a plan, but some way of attack to maybe stop some of the growth moving out of the city?
Because Plano is on the up and all the other suburbs to the north.
Yeah.
We started the North Dallas study with cooperation from the surrounding cities in that area.
I think there's seven cities that were involved.
And one of the objectives in that study was to limit development rights.
Like our zoning ordinance is too liberal.
They can build very intense development under current zoning.
In certain areas up there are O2 districts and MF2.
districts of pretty high densities.
One of the objectives was to have the zoning ordinance correlate to current average development, because development intensity increases as it starts to be building out.
As land becomes more valuable, you have to build more units per acre, more square footage of office or retail per acre.
So they wanted to try to put a ceiling on that.
and put a ceiling on it just above the current average development and not the current allowable development.
However, the other cities didn't want to cooperate with doing that.
So that fell through.
That was one objective of the North Dallas study.
But that never happened.
And cooperation with other cities broke down.
The problem here is it's regional in nature.
You have so many jurisdictions involved.
If one city tightened up their development standards, the development would just go to one of the other cities.
It would encourage development to go further north instead of go elsewhere in the city.
So the only way you can accomplish a goal of cutting back development densities is for all the cities in the area to cooperate.
whereas they're not really cooperating.
Each one wants to get as much development and thereby get as much revenues as possible from what's happening up there.
They want all their fair share or more than their fair share.
So everybody's in competition, essentially, with the other.
They're just not going to do anything to stop the growth.
They're going to try to encourage it.
And the result is massive transportation problems.
And that was another objective of the North Dallas study to solve some of the transportation problems up there.
But you can't solve transportation problems in this little portion of Dallas when you have impacts coming from three sides that you don't have control over.
So all the planning department can essentially do is
analyze the problem, project traffic volumes, and determine how much money is needed to meet that future demand.
And it ends up that it's in the hundreds of millions of dollars in that one 30 square mile area.
I'm not real familiar on the facts and figures of North Dallas because I didn't work on it.
But in terms of planning, our role is
Basically, we analyze the situation.
We tell the decision makers what are the implications of what's happening and what we expect to happen.
And not in terms, or at least we haven't yet formulated a plan for the area.
We do have various land use concepts formulated.
And under each scenario, we have the impacts of each scenario in terms of traffic volumes, in terms of dollars, and transportation improvements.
But it's really up in the hands of the decision makers whether or not and when in RF we're going to ever put those kind of improvements up there.
We know we're going to need them to solve the congestion problems.
But the other side of the coin is that people can live with congestion or that when it becomes so congested, the development will go elsewhere, will go further north.
There's no easy way to put a cap on that growth.
And we can't divert it to other areas of Dallas.
We could have 20 years ago if we had stronger planning.
But we didn't.
I think a lot of that growth could have gone elsewhere.
But it got started up there.
Like three years ago, no one expected that kind of thing to happen that quickly.
As far as planning is concerned, we really can't control it or direct it.
We can just monitor it.
Stay one step behind it.
Monitor it and analyze implications from what's happening currently, gear our bond programs to address those problems.
But there's going to come a point where other citizens in Dallas are going to

probably vote such bond programs down because we're sinking all this money up in that one area and they're going to feel like they're being ignored or politically at some point there's not going to be the money put up there that's necessary for those improvements in my opinion so you're going to probably have a very long term problem up there
It could be that areas up there, if congestion gets too bad and there's no money to solve the problem, certain businesses due to congestion might fail and might move further north or someplace else.
There's a potential problem up there, all kinds of problems to solve.
Would you like a copy of any of these papers?
